<p>One of the reasons using ORM is - in my opinion - to prevent duplicate records in a table. To reach this it is possible to create foreign keys to link multiple tables together.</p>  <p>My problem is as follows:</p>  <p>Table 'addresses':</p>  <pre><code>+---------------+---------+------+-----+---------+----------------+ | Field         | Type    | Null | Key | Default | Extra          | +---------------+---------+------+-----+---------+----------------+ | id            | int(11) | NO   | PRI | NULL    | auto_increment | | country_id    | int(11) | NO   |     | NULL    |                | | city_id       | int(11) | NO   |     | NULL    |                | | street_id     | int(11) | NO   |     | NULL    |                | | zip_id        | int(11) | NO   |     | NULL    |                | | street_number | int(11) | NO   |     | NULL    |                | +---------------+---------+------+-----+---------+----------------+ </code></pre>  <p>Table 'countries':</p>  <pre><code>+-------+-------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+ | Field | Type        | Null | Key | Default | Extra          | +-------+-------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+ | id    | int(11)     | NO   | PRI | NULL    | auto_increment | | name  | varchar(45) | NO   | UNI | NULL    |                | +-------+-------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+ </code></pre>  <p>(same logic to the other tables)</p>  <p>When I try to save an entry with a country-name which already exist I'll get an mysql unique error. This is clear and absolutely okay. Everything works as intended.</p>  <p>The question is: What is the best practice to save entities with (unique) associations which already exists and how is it possible to get the id (foreign key) of the existing (e.g. country.id) to link it in the addresses table?</p>  <p>Is there any cake-magic which fits for my case?</p>  <p>Thanks in advance,</p>  <p>Phil</p>